    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-02T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-02T07:00:00-05:00" n="379"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d379">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/3248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d379fn4">Forwarded to the Commission to Negotiate Peace,
                        Jan. 6, 1919, 3 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-02T21:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 2, 1919—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 2—6:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In a contribution to the <hi rend="italic">Kokumin</hi> of January 1st, Marquis
                    Okuma states that permanent peace cannot be achieved without first solving the
                    question of the equality of treatment of races and the question of armaments. He
                    asks how America proposes to treat in future the alien races in her territory,
                    and expresses the hope that American public opinion will adopt a generous
                    attitude toward this question. At the same time he insists that Japanese
                    emigrants be freely allowed to enter every country. He further hopes that in
                    order to act [<hi rend="italic">secure</hi>] a permanent peace the powers will
                    avoid severe tariff wars. In connection with the question of armaments, the
                    Marquis asks how America’s new naval program and Great Britain’s insistence on
                    naval supremacy can be reconciled with the declarations of these countries. He
                    hopes that the press reports to the effect that Congress has disapproved of
                    President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>’s fourteen fundamental
                    terms are without foundation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
